
- change path of satay.sh to the /data/localhome/username/
- make a folder structure as follows:
├── reference_sequences
│   └── Cerevisiae_S288C_reference
└── software
    ├── python_codes (folder python_transposonmapping from LaanLab-SATAY-DataAnalysis)
    │   ├── data_files (folder data_files from LaanLab-SATAY-DataAnalysis))
    │   └── python_modules
    
  


Installing applications
- yap
- FASTQC 
	sudo apt install fastqc (https://command-not-found.com/fastqc)
- BBMAP
	- the extracted folder is just copied to the a folder inside software
- BWA
	- the link in the document does not point to the installation folder 
	- go to the source-forge page and onces downloaded do :
		sudo apt install bwa
- SAMTOOLs
	- download the zip folder
	- sudo apt install samtools
- sambamba-0.7.1-linux-static
	- sudo apt install sambamba 
		- sambamba 0.6.7-pre1
	- see a whole set of instructions here : https://github.com/biod/sambamba/issues/195#issuecomment-197495974

- pysam
	- pip install pysam

- Indexing the reference genome
  Two ways:
1- in the satay.sh
 	- add this line `bwa index reference_genome` in line 538 before comitting the alignment 
	echo 'Index reference genome ...'
		bwa index ${path_refgenome} 
	- then check your folder where the reference genome is and these files should be there:
└── Cerevisiae_S288C_reference
    ├── S288C_reference_sequence_R64-2-1_20150113.fsa
    ├── S288C_reference_sequence_R64-2-1_20150113.fsa.amb
    ├── S288C_reference_sequence_R64-2-1_20150113.fsa.ann
    ├── S288C_reference_sequence_R64-2-1_20150113.fsa.bwt
    ├── S288C_reference_sequence_R64-2-1_20150113.fsa.pac
    └── S288C_reference_sequence_R64-2-1_20150113.fsa.sa
2- run  the file satay_first_use.sh




